        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "**How it’s used here**\n\nIn this project, embeddings are used for semantic search, not for display or summarization directly.\n\nThe flow is:\n\n1. A capture is ingested and cleaned.\n2. The backend asks the LLM for a structured insight: title, summary, key points.\n3. The backend generates an embedding for the `summary`.\n4. That embedding is stored in PostgreSQL `pgvector`.\n5. When the user searches, the query text is also embedded, and the system compares the query vector to stored vectors using cosine similarity.\n\nYou can see that in:\n- [CaptureService.cs](/C:/ai-workspace/knowledgebase-platform/backend/src/SentinelKnowledgebase.Application/Services/CaptureService.cs#L217)\n- [CaptureService.cs](/C:/ai-workspace/knowledgebase-platform/backend/src/SentinelKnowledgebase.Application/Services/CaptureService.cs#L223)\n- [SearchService.cs](/C:/ai-workspace/knowledgebase-platform/backend/src/SentinelKnowledgebase.Application/Services/SearchService.cs#L19)\n- [ProcessedInsightRepository.cs](/C:/ai-workspace/knowledgebase-platform/backend/src/SentinelKnowledgebase.Infrastructure/Repositories/ProcessedInsightRepository.cs#L48)\n\n**What purpose it has**\n\nThe purpose is meaning-based retrieval.\n\nThat means a query like “posts about rate cuts” can match stored content whose summary says “the Fed may lower interest rates soon”, even if the exact words differ. That is the core reason embeddings exist in this repo.\n\nThe data model for that is:\n- `ProcessedInsight` holds the normalized AI summary: [ProcessedInsight.cs](/C:/ai-workspace/knowledgebase-platform/backend/src/SentinelKnowledgebase.Domain/Entities/ProcessedInsight.cs#L20)\n- `EmbeddingVector` holds the vector used for similarity search: [EmbeddingVector.cs](/C:/ai-workspace/knowledgebase-platform/backend/src/SentinelKnowledgebase.Domain/Entities/EmbeddingVector.cs#L7)\n- PostgreSQL has `pgvector` enabled and stores `vector(1536)`: [ApplicationDbContext.cs](/C:/ai-workspace/knowledgebase-platform/backend/src/SentinelKnowledgebase.Infrastructure/Data/ApplicationDbContext.cs#L33), [ApplicationDbContext.cs](/C:/ai-workspace/knowledgebase-platform/backend/src/SentinelKnowledgebase.Infrastructure/Data/ApplicationDbContext.cs#L168)\n\nThe repo docs say the same at a high level:\n- [README.md](/C:/ai-workspace/knowledgebase-platform/README.md)\n- [ENTITY-MODEL.md](/C:/ai-workspace/knowledgebase-platform/docs/ENTITY-MODEL.md#L237)\n\n**About “a single word producing 1572 vectors”**\n\nIt doesn’t produce 1572 vectors. It produces one vector with many dimensions.\n\nIn this project, that size is **1536**, not 1572:\n- [README.md](/C:/ai-workspace/knowledgebase-platform/README.md)\n- [appsettings.json](/C:/ai-workspace/knowledgebase-platform/backend/src/SentinelKnowledgebase.Api/appsettings.json#L42)\n- [EmbeddingVector.cs](/C:/ai-workspace/knowledgebase-platform/backend/src/SentinelKnowledgebase.Domain/Entities/EmbeddingVector.cs#L18)\n\nWhy can one word still become a 1536-dimensional vector?\n\nBecause embedding size is fixed by the model architecture. The model maps any input text, whether it is:\n- one word\n- one sentence\n- one paragraph\n\ninto one dense numeric representation of the same length.\n\nSo:\n- input length changes\n- meaning changes\n- output dimension stays fixed\n\nAlso, one word may tokenize into multiple subword tokens internally, but the embedding endpoint still returns one final fixed-length embedding for the whole input string.\n\nOne important project-specific detail: the code allows an optional `OpenAI:EmbeddingDimensions` request setting when calling the API, but the database schema is fixed to `vector(1536)`. So this codebase effectively expects 1536-dimensional embeddings end to end:\n- [ContentProcessor.cs](/C:/ai-workspace/knowledgebase-platform/backend/src/SentinelKnowledgebase.Application/Services/ContentProcessor.cs#L213)\n- [ContentProcessor.cs](/C:/ai-workspace/knowledgebase-platform/backend/src/SentinelKnowledgebase.Application/Services/ContentProcessor.cs#L230)\n- [ApplicationDbContext.cs](/C:/ai-workspace/knowledgebase-platform/backend/src/SentinelKnowledgebase.Infrastructure/Data/ApplicationDbContext.cs#L172)\n\nNo files changed. If you want, I can next explain the cosine similarity part with a concrete toy example using 3D vectors first, then map that back to the 1536D case.",
