        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Not fully.\n\nEmbeddings are often **partly multilingual**, meaning similar meanings in different languages can land near each other in vector space, but they are not perfectly language-neutral. In practice:\n\n- Simple cross-language concepts often match reasonably well.\n- Performance is usually better in high-resource languages like English.\n- Nuance, slang, domain jargon, and morphology can reduce cross-language alignment.\n- Mixed-language search usually works, but not as reliably as same-language search.\n\nFor this project, that means semantic search can probably retrieve related content across languages to some extent, but you should not assume “Czech query vs English stored summaries” will be as strong as “English vs English”.\n\nThere is also a project-specific constraint: the pipeline embeds the **AI-generated summary**, not the raw capture, in [CaptureService.cs](/C:/ai-workspace/knowledgebase-platform/backend/src/SentinelKnowledgebase.Application/Services/CaptureService.cs#L223). So cross-language behavior depends on what language that summary ends up in. If summaries are normalized into one language, retrieval becomes more consistent. If summaries remain in the source language, search quality becomes more language-dependent.\n\nShort version: embeddings are **meaning-aware across languages**, but not truly language-neutral.",
          "timestamp": "2026-04-08T22:48:46.222Z"
        },
        {
          "type": "user",
          "text": "I see. There are couple of things I was considering and embedding might help me here.\n\nI was thinking about assigning tags to insights based on topics etc. But this information might be already present in the embeddings?\n\nCould we use embeddings to make clusters of related information?",
          "timestamp": "2026-04-09T07:04:53.474Z"
